40|$|In {{this study}} we {{investigate}} how top management <b>pay</b> <b>is</b> determined in a family firm environment where even listed firms are effectively controlled by a single individual or a single family. Using data from Hong Kong, we find that executive directors 2 ̆ 7 <b>pay</b> <b>is</b> reduced if the directors have substantial stockholdings. Moreover, <b>pay</b> <b>is</b> related to profits but not to stock returns. Our {{results are consistent with}} external blockholders and independent non-executive directors persuading firms to base top management compensation on a firm 2 ̆ 7 s profitability...|$|R
