40|$|AbstractThis paper {{examines}} {{the effects of}} board affiliation on the corporate pay gap. Using a sample of Chinese listed firms from 2005 to 2011, we find that boards with a greater presence of directors appointed by block shareholders have lower pay gaps. Furthermore, the governance effects of board affiliation with and without <b>pay</b> <b>are</b> distinguished. The empirical results show that board affiliation without <b>pay</b> <b>is</b> negatively related to the pay gap, while board affiliation with <b>pay</b> <b>is</b> positively related to the pay gap. Overall, the results shed light on how block shareholders affect their companies’ pay gaps through board affiliation...|$|R
